1. # **Introduction**

Agentic-AI systems have improved its sophistication and ability to target IofT, individual consumer devices, and enterprise-grade environments. The October 2025 revelation by Anthropic offered a deeply distributing trend. Agentic-AI has now increased in its sophistication to the point that it can orchestrate mass-level large-scale attacks directed at consumer devices and local development environments. This has created an unprecedented effect on the local consumer market and has created a highly needed new demand of AI-enab;ed sophisticated anti-virus software. It has also created a markedly new shift in consumer demand from tech-savvy individual developers to everyday normal consumers to manipulate, control, and modify their local cyber-security environment in new and changing ways. 

However, this has been met with a range of challenges. Firstly, consumer level devices and environments are unlike their enterprise-level counterparts. Limited hardware capacity, coupled with low level understanding of consumers to cyber-architecture, even highly developer-trained individuals, pose unique challenges to this market. 

Secondly, using what is known as ‘AI only’ malware detection is both costly and inefficient to run on consumer grade-devices. Regular consumer environments simply do not have the level of RAM, processing power, and generally speaking, computing power to assess massive amounts of surveillance information on a large scale. While individual viral and malware patterned anomalies can be detected using traditional software, no anti-virus software has been developed to allow a consumer-level user to both utilize enterprise level threat-detection capabilities while simultaneously delivering a level of environmental control and customization that is seamless and understandable for the every-day consumer. 

Therefore, this project focuses chiefly on the democratization of cyber-security resources to the everyday consumer, coupled with AI to achieve cyber-accessibility. This is the first known research project that focuses on cyber-accessibility through the use of AI and architectural methods to allow for the capabilities of enterprise-level cyber-software to the every-day consumer using AI smartly as a client-sided accessibility interface, and dually, using the ML capabilities of an AI’s LLM for wide-ranging threat detection adapted to the every-day non-technical consumer. It corroborates both the natural language orientation and adaptive capabilities of ML and AI with the traditional infrastructural rules-based and pattern-based capability of enterprise-level anti-virus software adapted into a consumer-level interface channel.

This project explores the use of the Wazuh Open-source Platform to create an adaptive MCP interface for AI-enabled policy manipulation on a local deployment environment.
